      <DIV class=3Dposts><A name=3D1969347607840480943></A>
      <H2><FONT color=3D#000080><!-- 2004-09-02 -->OOXML+ODF: ISO Steps =
In=20
      </FONT></H2>
      <P>
      <DIV style=3D"CLEAR: both"></DIV>
      <P></P>
      <DIV class=3DwlWriterSmartContent=20
      =
id=3Dscid:0767317B-992E-4b12-91E0-4F059A8CECA8:dd747af6-d438-46a0-8ba4-1c=
afb2f2d37a=20
      style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0px; DISPLAY: inline; PADDING-LEFT: 0px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 0px; MARGIN: 0px; PADDING-TOP: 0px">Technorati=20
      Tags: <A href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/OOXML" =
rel=3Dtag>OOXML</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/ODF-OOXML%20Harmonization"=20
      rel=3Dtag>ODF-OOXML Harmonization</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/ODF" rel=3Dtag>ODF</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Oasis" rel=3Dtag>Oasis</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Ecma" rel=3Dtag>Ecma</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/ISO/IEC%20JTC1" =
rel=3Dtag>ISO/IEC JTC1</A>,=20
      <A href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/SC34" rel=3Dtag>SC34</A>, <A =

      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Alex%20Brown" rel=3Dtag>Alex =
Brown</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Rick%20Jelliffe" rel=3Dtag>Rick =

      Jelliffe</A></DIV>
      <P></P>
      <P>Clippings from the <A title=3D"Diary of nfoWorks-related =
activity"=20
      href=3D"http://nfoworks.org/nfoDiary.htm">nfoWorks Diary</A> on =
recent=20
      events of possible wider interest to standards geeks and armchair =
torch=20
      followers:</P>
      <DL>
        <DT><B><A title=3D"2008-04-09 Diary Entry: ISO/IEC Takes Over =
OOXML"=20
        =
href=3D"http://nfoworks.org/notes/2008/03/n080301d1.htm#2008-04-09">2008-=
04-09</A>=20
        ISO/IEC SC34 Takes Over OOXML</B>=20
        <DD>ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1 (JTC1) Subcommittee 34 =
(SC34)=20
        held a plenary meeting in Oslo, Norway on April 5-9.&nbsp; Alex =
Brown=20
        provides a <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://adjb.net/index.php?entry=3Dentry080409-221633">comprehensi=
ve=20
        report</A>.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; SC34 proposes to create ongoing =
activities=20
        to carry out its=20
        responsibilities:<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =
1. IS=20
        29500 (OOXML) =
maintenance<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        2. IS 26300 (ODF) maintenance (pending OASIS=20
        agreement)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3.=20
        Harmonization (with a proposed work-item expected from the DIN =
NIA=20
        activity)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; To start things off, two <I>ad hoc</I> =
working=20
        groups have been created.&nbsp; <BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; The first <I>ad =
hoc</I>=20
        working group will propose how IS 29500 maintenance should =
proceed,=20
        producing a proposal by 2008-09-01, one month prior to the next =
SC34=20
        meeting.&nbsp; This <I>ad hoc</I> group is chaired by Alex Brown =
who=20
        will lead a two-day meeting in London this July.&nbsp; =
Participation is=20
        from SC34 member bodies and I take it that ECMA TC45 members are =
invited=20
        to chime in.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; The second <I>ad hoc</I> working =
group is=20
        being created to capture technical comments on IS 29500 and make =
sure=20
        existing analysis is not lost.&nbsp; Within 90 days (by July 2) =
there=20
        will be a mechanism in operation "to compile a list of comments =
on=20
        ISO/IEC 29500 received from NBs, liaisons, and the general =
public" and=20
        then to "publish the on-going list as an open document on the SC =
34=20
        website."<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; In the<A=20
        href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/1025.htm"> =
resolutions from=20
        the meeting</A>, I note that the final text of DIS 29500 has =
already=20
        been created.&nbsp; SC 34 requests distribution to its members =
no later=20
        than May 1.&nbsp; I don't know what the delay will be before =
publication=20
        as IS 29500:2008 happens, and I'll beg a copy of the final DIS =
29500=20
        before that just to make sure I don't step into some element of=20
        harmonization that is impacted by BRM-approved changes =
(especially the=20
        various conformance statements that are new in the final =
text).&nbsp;=20
        Also, to make any contributions to identification of defects, it =
is=20
        important to reference the most-authoritative available =
documents.=20
        <BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; Here's what it looks like for intercepting =
DIS/IS 29500=20
        activity:<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1. =
Usable final=20
        text available in May for provisional use (if it can be =
obtained) until=20
        official IS 29500 editions are=20
        issued<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2. =
Mechanism for=20
        receiving defects and related comments on IS 29500 operating in=20
        July.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3. In =
September,=20
        2008, SC 34 meets in Korea and takes next steps, with meetings =
every six=20
        months (figure March 2009 in Prague, September 2009 in U.S., =
then 2010=20
        meetings in Sweden, then South Africa).<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; Working =
groups=20
        that will be doing the technical work are yet to be set up and =
they will=20
        have their own meetings, conference calls, and mailing lists as =
well as=20
        ones synchronized with SC34.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; (I have a current =
passport=20
        with lots of room for visa stamps.&nbsp; Now I just need a =
sponsor for=20
        expenses/subsistence and a national body to nominate me to a=20
        committee.&nbsp; Hint, hint.) <I>-- dh</I><BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <DT><B><A=20
        title=3D"2008-04-10 Diary Entry: Rick Jelliffe Perspective on =
SC34 Activity"=20
        =
href=3D"http://nfoworks.org/notes/2008/03/n080301d1.htm#2008-04-10">2008-=
04-10</A>=20
        Rick Jelliffe Perspective on SC34 Activity</B>=20
        <DD>Rick Jelliffe has a great perspective on the just-concluded =
SC34=20
        plenary meeting.&nbsp; Because he wasn't there, he offers it in =
a "<A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.oreillynet.com/xml/blog/2008/04/fake_blog_from_sc34_me=
eting_in.html">Fake=20
        blog from SC34 meeting in Norway</A>."&nbsp; Jelliffe offers up =
some=20
        important items to hold onto=20
        here:<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1. The main =
<A=20
        href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/">SC34 web site</A> =
(hosted in=20
        Japan by the SC34=20
        Secretariat)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2. =
The page=20
        for accessing public <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://lucia.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/itscj/servlets/ScmDoc10?Com_Id=3D34=
">SC34=20
        documents</A> (rewards=20
        exploration)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3. A =
reminder=20
        that TrueType is connected with the ISO/IEC Open Type standard,=20
        maintained in SC34 (and relevant for <I><B>nfoWorks</B></I>) =
with a=20
        hidden reminder that getting Asian scripts right is probably one =
of the=20
        best demonstrations of harmonization=20
        going.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4. An =
useful sketch=20
        of SC34's interests and=20
        responsibilities<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =
5.=20
        Another reminder of my own armchair critic status, something I =
am=20
        working to alter<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =
6. A=20
        discussion of the criticality of accessibility considerations =
and the=20
        resources that apply in the work of SC34 -- a topic that it will =
be=20
        essential to address with regard to=20
        harmonization<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 7. =
An=20
        injunction to become involved and where to do that (OASIS, W3C, =
Ecma=20
        TC45, the national mirror of SC34 in your neighborhood,=20
        etc.)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 8. Links to =
the DIN=20
        NIA-34 update on the harmonization investigation (<A=20
        href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/1026.pdf">PDF =
file</A>),=20
        great work that <I><B>nfoWorks</B></I> should align=20
        with<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9. An =
interesting=20
        side comment about the use of topic maps to present ODF-OOXML =
mappings=20
        (although DIN is focused on translations, not mappings, because =
of a=20
        number of issues that translation surfaces, including round-trip =

        degradation in collaboration=20
        scenarios)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10. =
Another=20
        side comment on how the concern for synchronizing ECMA versions =
and SC34=20
        versions of OOXML might be extended to the case of OASIS and ODF =
as=20
        well.</DD></DL>
      <HR>
      <SMALL>
      <P>I do know how to become engaged in this work (and my passport =
is indeed=20
      current), especially with regard to the prospects for document=20
      interoperability through harmonization.&nbsp;&nbsp; In the United =
States,=20
      the mirror activity would be in a working group of INCITS =
Technical=20
      Committee V1.&nbsp; (There might even be a liaison function with =
an=20
      association such as AIIM, because of the impact on content=20
      management.)&nbsp; The subsistence and sponsorship part is more =
difficult=20
      because my retirement can't cover it.&nbsp; Consistent with <A=20
      href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/03/on-giving-away.asp">giving =
it=20
      away</A> and not wanting to account to a commercial interest, I =
need to=20
      come up with some sort of neutral but generous affiliation.&nbsp; =
I could=20
      also reconcile myself to just collecting and building tools and=20
      collaboration via e-mail and distribution list.&nbsp; Others can =
pick up=20
      on that or not, in an open-source development spirit.&nbsp; =
Ponder,=20
      ponder, ponder, ...</P>
      <P>I was rather proud of myself in creating the nfoWorks Diary and =
using=20
      it to reflect progress in that area on a daily basis.&nbsp; It is =
easy to=20
      write there because I am busy in my web-site editor already.&nbsp; =
But it=20
      is not very participative.&nbsp; There is no feed, even though it =
is a=20
      form of web log, and there is no provision for commentary.&nbsp; =
Slight=20
      consolation: you can comment here, and I will always receive =
notice of=20
      it.&nbsp; I'll also see de.licio.us for:orcmid.&nbsp; It would be =
great to=20
      have an nfoWare wiki though.&nbsp; That is somewhere down the road =
to=20
      someday.</P></SMALL>
